resources.string:
Create a new resources .xml file in /res/values like a copy of strings.xml
 put a new resource with known parameter, like "textFromFile" and later yours text
 Assign a value "textView" to our textBox in xml
 TextView textView = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.defaultText);
 Set value "textView" from file to our object.
 textView.setText(R.string.textFromFile);

Create method which opens ActivityName
 public void methodName (View view) {
 Intent intentName = new Intent(this, ActivityName.class);
 startActivity(intentName);
 Apply this method to onClick properties in .xml

In main activity create constant to hold string code (to recognise each values)
 public static final String MESSAGE_KEY = "Value from main activity";
 Create intent to open new activity
 Intent intentName = new Intent(this, ActivityName.class);
 Read value from main activity to some EditText
 EditText editText = (EditText) findViewById(R.id.editText);
 Put that value into variable as String (or what kind do you need)
 String message = editText.getText().toString();
 Put that variable to intent object with correct key and related with it variable
 intent.putExtra(MESSAGE_KEY, message);
 Start new activity
 startActivity(intentName);

Create a TextView to read a value
 Get the Intent that started this activity and extract the string
 Intent intentName = getIntent();
 String message = intentName.getStringExtra(MainActivity.MESSAGE_KEY);

Capture the layouts TextView and set the string as its text
 TextView textView = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.textView);
 textView.setText(message);

In case of some default themes on each activity,
 you cannot see a overflow menu icon
 1. Create a menu.xml resource file in /res/menu/
 Paste:
 item
 android:id="@+id/action_function"
 android:icon="@drawable/icon"
 android:title="@string/action_string_name"
 app:showAsAction="ifRoom"/
 2. Put a below method in activity where you want a overflow menu 
 public boolean onCreateOptionsMenu(Menu menu) { 
 MenuInflater inflater = getMenuInflater(); 
 inflater.inflate(R.menu.menu, menu); 
 return true; 
 }

Simply toast with some options: 
 Toast toast = new Toast(getApplicationContext()); 
 toast.setGravity(Gravity.CENTER_VERTICAL, 0, 0); 
 toast.setDuration(Toast.LENGTH_LONG); 
 toast.setView(layout); 
 toast.show(); 

 Default toast on middle of screen: 
 Toast.makeText(getApplicationContext(), "text", Toast.LENGTH_LONG).show();

Set a static value (display time in miliseconds)

 public static int SPLASH_TIME_OUT = 3000;

 Write on onCreate method:

 new Handler().postDelayed(new Runnable() {
 @Override
 public void run() {
 Intent splashIntent = new Intent(SplashScreen.this, MainMenu.class);
 startActivity(splashIntent);
 finish();
 }
 },SPLASH_TIME_OUT);
